44Ac 13:39 Through him everyone who believes is justified from everything you could not be justified from by the law of Moses.
44Ac 13:40 Take care that what the prophets have said does not happen to you£º
44Ac 13:41 "'Look, you scoffers, wonder and perish, for I am going to do something in your days that you would never believe, even if someone told you.'"
44Ac 13:42 As Paul and Barnabas were leaving the synagogue, the people invited them to speak further about these things on the next Sabbath.
44Ac 13:43 When the congregation was dismissed, many of the Jews and devout converts to Judaism followed Paul and Barnabas, who talked with them and urged them to continue in the grace of God.
44Ac 13:44 On the next Sabbath almost the whole city gathered to hear the word of the Lord.
44Ac 13:45 When the Jews saw the crowds, they were filled with jealousy and talked abusively against what Paul was saying.
44Ac 13:46 Then Paul and Barnabas answered them boldly£º "We had to speak the word of God to you first. Since you reject it and do not consider yourselves worthy of eternal life, we now turn to the Gentiles.
44Ac 13:47 For this is what the Lord has commanded us£º "'I have made you a light for the Gentiles, that you may bring salvation to the ends of the earth.'"
44Ac 13:48 When the Gentiles heard this, they were glad and honored the word of the Lord; and all who were appointed for eternal life believed.
44Ac 13:49 The word of the Lord spread through the whole region.
44Ac 13:50 But the Jews incited the God-fearing women of high standing and the leading men of the city. They stirred up persecution against Paul and Barnabas, and expelled them from their region.
44Ac 13:51 So they shook the dust from their feet in protest against them and went to Iconium.
44Ac 13:52 And the disciples were filled with joy and with the Holy Spirit.
44Ac 14:1 At Iconium Paul and Barnabas went as usual into the Jewish synagogue. There they spoke so effectively that a great number of Jews and Gentiles believed.
44Ac 14:2 But the Jews who refused to believe stirred up the Gentiles and poisoned their minds against the brothers.
44Ac 14:3 So Paul and Barnabas spent considerable time there, speaking boldly for the Lord, who confirmed the message of his grace by enabling them to do miraculous signs and wonders.
44Ac 14:4 The people of the city were divided; some sided with the Jews, others with the apostles.
44Ac 14:5 There was a plot afoot among the Gentiles and Jews, together with their leaders, to mistreat them and stone them.
44Ac 14:6 But they found out about it and fled to the Lycaonian cities of Lystra and Derbe and to the surrounding country,
44Ac 14:7 where they continued to preach the good news.
44Ac 14:8 In Lystra there sat a man crippled in his feet, who was lame from birth and had never walked.
44Ac 14:9 He listened to Paul as he was speaking. Paul looked directly at him, saw that he had faith to be healed
44Ac 14:10 and called out, "Stand up on your feet!" At that, the man jumped up and began to walk.
44Ac 14:11 When the crowd saw what Paul had done, they shouted in the Lycaonian language, "The gods have come down to us in human form!"
44Ac 14:12 Barnabas they called Zeus, and Paul they called Hermes because he was the chief speaker.
44Ac 14:13 The priest of Zeus, whose temple was just outside the city, brought bulls and wreaths to the city gates because he and the crowd wanted to offer sacrifices to them.
44Ac 14:14 But when the apostles Barnabas and Paul heard of this, they tore their clothes and rushed out into the crowd, shouting£º
44Ac 14:15 "Men, why are you doing this? We too are only men, human like you. We are bringing you good news, telling you to turn from these worthless things to the living God, who made heaven and earth and sea and everything in them.
44Ac 14:16 In the past, he let all nations go their own way.
44Ac 14:17 Yet he has not left himself without testimony£º He has shown kindness by giving you rain from heaven and crops in their seasons; he provides you with plenty of food and fills your hearts with joy."
44Ac 14:18 Even with these words, they had difficulty keeping the crowd from sacrificing to them.
44Ac 14:19 Then some Jews came from Antioch and Iconium and won the crowd over. They stoned Paul and dragged him outside the city, thinking he was dead.
44Ac 14:20 But after the disciples had gathered around him, he got up and went back into the city. The next day he and Barnabas left for Derbe.
44Ac 14:21 They preached the good news in that city and won a large number of disciples. Then they returned to Lystra, Iconium and Antioch,
44Ac 14:22 strengthening the disciples and encouraging them to remain true to the faith. "We must go through many hardships to enter the kingdom of God," they said.
44Ac 14:23 Paul and Barnabas appointed elders for them in each church and, with prayer and fasting, committed them to the Lord, in whom they had put their trust.
44Ac 14:24 After going through Pisidia, they came into Pamphylia,
44Ac 14:25 and when they had preached the word in Perga, they went down to Attalia.
44Ac 14:26 From Attalia they sailed back to Antioch, where they had been committed to the grace of God for the work they had now completed.
44Ac 14:27 On arriving there, they gathered the church together and reported all that God had done through them and how he had opened the door of faith to the Gentiles.
44Ac 14:28 And they stayed there a long time with the disciples.
44Ac 15:1 Some men came down from Judea to Antioch and were teaching the brothers£º "Unless you are circumcised, according to the custom taught by Moses, you cannot be saved."
44Ac 15:2 This brought Paul and Barnabas into sharp dispute and debate with them. So Paul and Barnabas were appointed, along with some other believers, to go up to Jerusalem to see the apostles and elders about this question.
44Ac 15:3 The church sent them on their way, and as they traveled through Phoenicia and Samaria, they told how the Gentiles had been converted. This news made all the brothers very glad.
44Ac 15:4 When they came to Jerusalem, they were welcomed by the church and the apostles and elders, to whom they reported everything God had done through them.
44Ac 15:5 Then some of the believers who belonged to the party of the Pharisees stood up and said, "The Gentiles must be circumcised and required to obey the law of Moses."
44Ac 15:6 The apostles and elders met to consider this question.
44Ac 15:7 After much discussion, Peter got up and addressed them£º "Brothers, you know that some time ago God made a choice among you that the Gentiles might hear from my lips the message of the gospel and believe.
44Ac 15:8 God, who knows the heart, showed that he accepted them by giving the Holy Spirit to them, just as he did to us.
44Ac 15:9 He made no distinction between us and them, for he purified their hearts by faith.
44Ac 15:10 Now then, why do you try to test God by putting on the necks of the disciples a yoke that neither we nor our fathers have been able to bear?
44Ac 15:11 No! We believe it is through the grace of our Lord Jesus that we are saved, just as they are."
44Ac 15:12 The whole assembly became silent as they listened to Barnabas and Paul telling about the miraculous signs and wonders God had done among the Gentiles through them.
44Ac 15:13 When they finished, James spoke up£º "Brothers, listen to me.
44Ac 15:14 Simon has described to us how God at first showed his concern by taking from the Gentiles a people for himself.
44Ac 15:15 The words of the prophets are in agreement with this, as it is written£º
44Ac 15:16 "'After this I will return and rebuild David's fallen tent. Its ruins I will rebuild, and I will restore it,
44Ac 15:17 that the remnant of men may seek the Lord, and all the Gentiles who bear my name, says the Lord, who does these things'
44Ac 15:18 that have been known for ages.
44Ac 15:19 "It is my judgment, therefore, that we should not make it difficult for the Gentiles who are turning to God.
44Ac 15:20 Instead we should write to them, telling them to abstain from food polluted by idols, from sexual immorality, from the meat of strangled animals and from blood.
44Ac 15:21 For Moses has been preached in every city from the earliest times and is read in the synagogues on every Sabbath."
44Ac 15:22 Then the apostles and elders, with the whole church, decided to choose some of their own men and send them to Antioch with Paul and Barnabas. They chose Judas (called Barsabbas) and Silas, two men who were leaders among the brothers.
44Ac 15:23 With them they sent the following letter£º The apostles and elders, your brothers, To the Gentile believers in Antioch, Syria and Cilicia£º Greetings.
44Ac 15:24 We have heard that some went out from us without our authorization and disturbed you, troubling your minds by what they said.
44Ac 15:25 So we all agreed to choose some men and send them to you with our dear friends Barnabas and Paul--
44Ac 15:26 men who have risked their lives for the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.
44Ac 15:27 Therefore we are sending Judas and Silas to confirm by word of mouth what we are writing.
44Ac 15:28 It seemed good to the Holy Spirit and to us not to burden you with anything beyond the following requirements£º
44Ac 15:29 You are to abstain from food sacrificed to idols, from blood, from the meat of strangled animals and from sexual immorality. You will do well to avoid these things. Farewell.
44Ac 15:30 The men were sent off and went down to Antioch, where they gathered the church together and delivered the letter.
44Ac 15:31 The people read it and were glad for its encouraging message.
44Ac 15:32 Judas and Silas, who themselves were prophets, said much to encourage and strengthen the brothers.
44Ac 15:33 After spending some time there, they were sent off by the brothers with the blessing of peace to return to those who had sent them.
44Ac 15:34 But Silas decided to remain there.
44Ac 15:35 But Paul and Barnabas remained in Antioch, where they and many others taught and preached the word of the Lord.
44Ac 15:36 Some time later Paul said to Barnabas, "Let us go back and visit the brothers in all the towns where we preached the word of the Lord and see how they are doing."
44Ac 15:37 Barnabas wanted to take John, also called Mark, with them,
44Ac 15:38 but Paul did not think it wise to take him, because he had deserted them in Pamphylia and had not continued with them in the work.
44Ac 15:39 They had such a sharp disagreement that they parted company. Barnabas took Mark and sailed for Cyprus,
44Ac 15:40 but Paul chose Silas and left, commended by the brothers to the grace of the Lord.
44Ac 15:41 He went through Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the churches.
44Ac 16:1 He came to Derbe and then to Lystra, where a disciple named Timothy lived, whose mother was a Jewess and a believer, but whose father was a Greek.
44Ac 16:2 The brothers at Lystra and Iconium spoke well of him.
44Ac 16:3 Paul wanted to take him along on the journey, so he circumcised him because of the Jews who lived in that area, for they all knew that his father was a Greek.
44Ac 16:4 As they traveled from town to town, they delivered the decisions reached by the apostles and elders in Jerusalem for the people to obey.
44Ac 16:5 So the churches were strengthened in the faith and grew daily in numbers.
44Ac 16:6 Paul and his companions traveled throughout the region of Phrygia and Galatia, having been kept by the Holy Spirit from preaching the word in the province of Asia.
44Ac 16:7 When they came to the border of Mysia, they tried to enter Bithynia, but the Spirit of Jesus would not allow them to.
44Ac 16:8 So they passed by Mysia and went down to Troas.
44Ac 16:9 During the night Paul had a vision of a man of Macedonia standing and begging him, "Come over to Macedonia and help us."
44Ac 16:10 After Paul had seen the vision, we got ready at once to leave for Macedonia, concluding that God had called us to preach the gospel to them.
44Ac 16:11 From Troas we put out to sea and sailed straight for Samothrace, and the next day on to Neapolis.
44Ac 16:12 From there we traveled to Philippi, a Roman colony and the leading city of that district of Macedonia. And we stayed there several days.
44Ac 16:13 On the Sabbath we went outside the city gate to the river, where we expected to find a place of prayer. We sat down and began to speak to the women who had gathered there.
44Ac 16:14 One of those listening was a woman named Lydia, a dealer in purple cloth from the city of Thyatira, who was a worshiper of God. The Lord opened her heart to respond to Paul's message.
44Ac 16:15 When she and the members of her household were baptized, she invited us to her home. "If you consider me a believer in the Lord," she said, "come and stay at my house." And she persuaded us.
44Ac 16:16 Once when we were going to the place of prayer, we were met by a slave girl who had a spirit by which she predicted the future. She earned a great deal of money for her owners by fortune-telling.
44Ac 16:17 This girl followed Paul and the rest of us, shouting, "These men are servants of the Most High God, who are telling you the way to be saved."
44Ac 16:18 She kept this up for many days. Finally Paul became so troubled that he turned around and said to the spirit, "In the name of Jesus Christ I command you to come out of her!" At that moment the spirit left her.
44Ac 16:19 When the owners of the slave girl realized that their hope of making money was gone, they seized Paul and Silas and dragged them into the marketplace to face the authorities.
44Ac 16:20 They brought them before the magistrates and said, "These men are Jews, and are throwing our city into an uproar
44Ac 16:21 by advocating customs unlawful for us Romans to accept or practice."
44Ac 16:22 The crowd joined in the attack against Paul and Silas, and the magistrates ordered them to be stripped and beaten.
44Ac 16:23 After they had been severely flogged, they were thrown into prison, and the jailer was commanded to guard them carefully.
44Ac 16:24 Upon receiving such orders, he put them in the inner cell and fastened their feet in the stocks.
44Ac 16:25 About midnight Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to God, and the other prisoners were listening to them.
44Ac 16:26 Suddenly there was such a violent earthquake that the foundations of the prison were shaken. At once all the prison doors flew open, and everybody's chains came loose.
44Ac 16:27 The jailer woke up, and when he saw the prison doors open, he drew his sword and was about to kill himself because he thought the prisoners had escaped.
44Ac 16:28 But Paul shouted, "Don't harm yourself! We are all here!"
44Ac 16:29 The jailer called for lights, rushed in and fell trembling before Paul and Silas.
44Ac 16:30 He then brought them out and asked, "Sirs, what must I do to be saved?"
44Ac 16:31 They replied, "Believe in the Lord Jesus, and you will be saved--you and your household."
44Ac 16:32 Then they spoke the word of the Lord to him and to all the others in his house.
44Ac 16:33 At that hour of the night the jailer took them and washed their wounds; then immediately he and all his family were baptized.
44Ac 16:34 The jailer brought them into his house and set a meal before them; he was filled with joy because he had come to believe in God--he and his whole family.
44Ac 16:35 When it was daylight, the magistrates sent their officers to the jailer with the order£º "Release those men."
44Ac 16:36 The jailer told Paul, "The magistrates have ordered that you and Silas be released. Now you can leave. Go in peace."
44Ac 16:37 But Paul said to the officers£º "They beat us publicly without a trial, even though we are Roman citizens, and threw us into prison. And now do they want to get rid of us quietly? No! Let them come themselves and escort us out."
44Ac 16:38 The officers reported this to the magistrates, and when they heard that Paul and Silas were Roman citizens, they were alarmed.
44Ac 16:39 They came to appease them and escorted them from the prison, requesting them to leave the city.
44Ac 16:40 After Paul and Silas came out of the prison, they went to Lydia's house, where they met with the brothers and encouraged them. Then they left.
44Ac 17:1 When they had passed through Amphipolis and Apollonia, they came to Thessalonica, where there was a Jewish synagogue.
44Ac 17:2 As his custom was, Paul went into the synagogue, and on three Sabbath days he reasoned with them from the Scriptures,
44Ac 17:3 explaining and proving that the Christ had to suffer and rise from the dead. "This Jesus I am proclaiming to you is the Christ," he said.
44Ac 17:4 Some of the Jews were persuaded and joined Paul and Silas, as did a large number of God-fearing Greeks and not a few prominent women.
44Ac 17:5 But the Jews were jealous; so they rounded up some bad characters from the marketplace, formed a mob and started a riot in the city. They rushed to Jason's house in search of Paul and Silas in order to bring them out to the crowd.
44Ac 17:6 But when they did not find them, they dragged Jason and some other brothers before the city officials, shouting£º "These men who have caused trouble all over the world have now come here,
44Ac 17:7 and Jason has welcomed them into his house. They are all defying Caesar's decrees, saying that there is another king, one called Jesus."
44Ac 17:8 When they heard this, the crowd and the city officials were thrown into turmoil.
44Ac 17:9 Then they made Jason and the others post bond and let them go.
44Ac 17:10 As soon as it was night, the brothers sent Paul and Silas away to Berea. On arriving there, they went to the Jewish synagogue.
44Ac 17:11 Now the Bereans were of more noble character than the Thessalonians, for they received the message with great eagerness and examined the Scriptures every day to see if what Paul said was true.
44Ac 17:12 Many of the Jews believed, as did also a number of prominent Greek women and many Greek men.
44Ac 17:13 When the Jews in Thessalonica learned that Paul was preaching the word of God at Berea, they went there too, agitating the crowds and stirring them up.
44Ac 17:14 The brothers immediately sent Paul to the coast, but Silas and Timothy stayed at Berea.
44Ac 17:15 The men who escorted Paul brought him to Athens and then left with instructions for Silas and Timothy to join him as soon as possible.
44Ac 17:16 While Paul was waiting for them in Athens, he was greatly distressed to see that the city was full of idols.
44Ac 17:17 So he reasoned in the synagogue with the Jews and the God-fearing Greeks, as well as in the marketplace day by day with those who happened to be there.
44Ac 17:18 A group of Epicurean and Stoic philosophers began to dispute with him. Some of them asked, "What is this babbler trying to say?" Others remarked, "He seems to be advocating foreign gods." They said this because Paul was preaching the good news about Jesus and the resurrection.
44Ac 17:19 Then they took him and brought him to a meeting of the Areopagus, where they said to him, "May we know what this new teaching is that you are presenting?
44Ac 17:20 You are bringing some strange ideas to our ears, and we want to know what they mean."
44Ac 17:21 (All the Athenians and the foreigners who lived there spent their time doing nothing but talking about and listening to the latest ideas.)
44Ac 17:22 Paul then stood up in the meeting of the Areopagus and said£º "Men of Athens! I see that in every way you are very religious.
44Ac 17:23 For as I walked around and looked carefully at your objects of worship, I even found an altar with this inscription£º TO AN UNKNOWN GOD. Now what you worship as something unknown I am going to proclaim to you.
44Ac 17:24 "The God who made the world and everything in it is the Lord of heaven and earth and does not live in temples built by hands.
44Ac 17:25 And he is not served by human hands, as if he needed anything, because he himself gives all men life and breath and everything else.
44Ac 17:26 From one man he made every nation of men, that they should inhabit the whole earth; and he determined the times set for them and the exact places where they should live.
44Ac 17:27 God did this so that men would seek him and perhaps reach out for him and find him, though he is not far from each one of us.
44Ac 17:28 'For in him we live and move and have our being.' As some of your own poets have said, 'We are his offspring.'
44Ac 17:29 "Therefore since we are God's offspring, we should not think that the divine being is like gold or silver or stone--an image made by man's design and skill.
44Ac 17:30 In the past God overlooked such ignorance, but now he commands all people everywhere to repent.
44Ac 17:31 For he has set a day when he will judge the world with justice by the man he has appointed. He has given proof of this to all men by raising him from the dead."
44Ac 17:32 When they heard about the resurrection of the dead, some of them sneered, but others said, "We want to hear you again on this subject."
44Ac 17:33 At that, Paul left the Council.
44Ac 17:34 A few men became followers of Paul and believed. Among them was Dionysius, a member of the Areopagus, also a woman named Damaris, and a number of others.
44Ac 18:1 After this, Paul left Athens and went to Corinth.
44Ac 18:2 There he met a Jew named Aquila, a native of Pontus, who had recently come from Italy with his wife Priscilla, because Claudius had ordered all the Jews to leave Rome. Paul went to see them,
44Ac 18:3 and because he was a tentmaker as they were, he stayed and worked with them.
44Ac 18:4 Every Sabbath he reasoned in the synagogue, trying to persuade Jews and Greeks.
44Ac 18:5 When Silas and Timothy came from Macedonia, Paul devoted himself exclusively to preaching, testifying to the Jews that Jesus was the Christ.
44Ac 18:6 But when the Jews opposed Paul and became abusive, he shook out his clothes in protest and said to them, "Your blood be on your own heads! I am clear of my responsibility. From now on I will go to the Gentiles."
44Ac 18:7 Then Paul left the synagogue and went next door to the house of Titius Justus, a worshiper of God.
44Ac 18:8 Crispus, the synagogue ruler, and his entire household believed in the Lord; and many of the Corinthians who heard him believed and were baptized.
44Ac 18:9 One night the Lord spoke to Paul in a vision£º "Do not be afraid; keep on speaking, do not be silent.
44Ac 18:10 For I am with you, and no one is going to attack and harm you, because I have many people in this city."
44Ac 18:11 So Paul stayed for a year and a half, teaching them the word of God.
44Ac 18:12 While Gallio was proconsul of Achaia, the Jews made a united attack on Paul and brought him into court.
44Ac 18:13 "This man," they charged, "is persuading the people to worship God in ways contrary to the law."
44Ac 18:14 Just as Paul was about to speak, Gallio said to the Jews, "If you Jews were making a complaint about some misdemeanor or serious crime, it would be reasonable for me to listen to you.
44Ac 18:15 But since it involves questions about words and names and your own law--settle the matter yourselves. I will not be a judge of such things."
44Ac 18:16 So he had them ejected from the court.
44Ac 18:17 Then they all turned on Sosthenes the synagogue ruler and beat him in front of the court. But Gallio showed no concern whatever.
44Ac 18:18 Paul stayed on in Corinth for some time. Then he left the brothers and sailed for Syria, accompanied by Priscilla and Aquila. Before he sailed, he had his hair cut off at Cenchrea because of a vow he had taken.
44Ac 18:19 They arrived at Ephesus, where Paul left Priscilla and Aquila. He himself went into the synagogue and reasoned with the Jews.
44Ac 18:20 When they asked him to spend more time with them, he declined.
44Ac 18:21 But as he left, he promised, "I will come back if it is God's will." Then he set sail from Ephesus.
44Ac 18:22 When he landed at Caesarea, he went up and greeted the church and then went down to Antioch.
44Ac 18:23 After spending some time in Antioch, Paul set out from there and traveled from place to place throughout the region of Galatia and Phrygia, strengthening all the disciples.
44Ac 18:24 Meanwhile a Jew named Apollos, a native of Alexandria, came to Ephesus. He was a learned man, with a thorough knowledge of the Scriptures.
44Ac 18:25 He had been instructed in the way of the Lord, and he spoke with great fervor and taught about Jesus accurately, though he knew only the baptism of John.
44Ac 18:26 He began to speak boldly in the synagogue. When Priscilla and Aquila heard him, they invited him to their home and explained to him the way of God more adequately.
44Ac 18:27 When Apollos wanted to go to Achaia, the brothers encouraged him and wrote to the disciples there to welcome him. On arriving, he was a great help to those who by grace had believed.
44Ac 18:28 For he vigorously refuted the Jews in public debate, proving from the Scriptures that Jesus was the Christ.
44Ac 19:1 While Apollos was at Corinth, Paul took the road through the interior and arrived at Ephesus. There he found some disciples
44Ac 19:2 and asked them, "Did you receive the Holy Spirit when you believed?" They answered, "No, we have not even heard that there is a Holy Spirit."
44Ac 19:3 So Paul asked, "Then what baptism did you receive?" "John's baptism," they replied.
44Ac 19:4 Paul said, "John's baptism was a baptism of repentance. He told the people to believe in the one coming after him, that is, in Jesus."
44Ac 19:5 On hearing this, they were baptized into the name of the Lord Jesus.
44Ac 19:6 When Paul placed his hands on them, the Holy Spirit came on them, and they spoke in tongues and prophesied.
44Ac 19:7 There were about twelve men in all.
44Ac 19:8 Paul entered the synagogue and spoke boldly there for three months, arguing persuasively about the kingdom of God.
44Ac 19:9 But some of them became obstinate; they refused to believe and publicly maligned the Way. So Paul left them. He took the disciples with him and had discussions daily in the lecture hall of Tyrannus.
44Ac 19:10 This went on for two years, so that all the Jews and Greeks who lived in the province of Asia heard the word of the Lord.
44Ac 19:11 God did extraordinary miracles through Paul,
44Ac 19:12 so that even handkerchiefs and aprons that had touched him were taken to the sick, and their illnesses were cured and the evil spirits left them.
44Ac 19:13 Some Jews who went around driving out evil spirits tried to invoke the name of the Lord Jesus over those who were demon-possessed. They would say, "In the name of Jesus, whom Paul preaches, I command you to come out."
44Ac 19:14 Seven sons of Sceva, a Jewish chief priest, were doing this.
44Ac 19:15 One day the evil spirit answered them, "Jesus I know, and I know about Paul, but who are you?"
44Ac 19:16 Then the man who had the evil spirit jumped on them and overpowered them all. He gave them such a beating that they ran out of the house naked and bleeding.
44Ac 19:17 When this became known to the Jews and Greeks living in Ephesus, they were all seized with fear, and the name of the Lord Jesus was held in high honor.
44Ac 19:18 Many of those who believed now came and openly confessed their evil deeds.
44Ac 19:19 A number who had practiced sorcery brought their scrolls together and burned them publicly. When they calculated the value of the scrolls, the total came to fifty thousand drachmas.
44Ac 19:20 In this way the word of the Lord spread widely and grew in power.
44Ac 19:21 After all this had happened, Paul decided to go to Jerusalem, passing through Macedonia and Achaia. "After I have been there," he said, "I must visit Rome also."
44Ac 19:22 He sent two of his helpers, Timothy and Erastus, to Macedonia, while he stayed in the province of Asia a little longer.
44Ac 19:23 About that time there arose a great disturbance about the Way.
44Ac 19:24 A silversmith named Demetrius, who made silver shrines of Artemis, brought in no little business for the craftsmen.
44Ac 19:25 He called them together, along with the workmen in related trades, and said£º "Men, you know we receive a good income from this business.
44Ac 19:26 And you see and hear how this fellow Paul has convinced and led astray large numbers of people here in Ephesus and in practically the whole province of Asia. He says that man-made gods are no gods at all.
44Ac 19:27 There is danger not only that our trade will lose its good name, but also that the temple of the great goddess Artemis will be discredited, and the goddess herself, who is worshiped throughout the province of Asia and the world, will be robbed of her divine majesty."
44Ac 19:28 When they heard this, they were furious and began shouting£º "Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!"
44Ac 19:29 Soon the whole city was in an uproar. The people seized Gaius and Aristarchus, Paul's traveling companions from Macedonia, and rushed as one man into the theater.
44Ac 19:30 Paul wanted to appear before the crowd, but the disciples would not let him.
44Ac 19:31 Even some of the officials of the province, friends of Paul, sent him a message begging him not to venture into the theater.
44Ac 19:32 The assembly was in confusion£º Some were shouting one thing, some another. Most of the people did not even know why they were there.
44Ac 19:33 The Jews pushed Alexander to the front, and some of the crowd shouted instructions to him. He motioned for silence in order to make a defense before the people.
44Ac 19:34 But when they realized he was a Jew, they all shouted in unison for about two hours£º "Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!"
44Ac 19:35 The city clerk quieted the crowd and said£º "Men of Ephesus, doesn't all the world know that the city of Ephesus is the guardian of the temple of the great Artemis and of her image, which fell from heaven?
44Ac 19:36 Therefore, since these facts are undeniable, you ought to be quiet and not do anything rash.
44Ac 19:37 You have brought these men here, though they have neither robbed temples nor blasphemed our goddess.
44Ac 19:38 If, then, Demetrius and his fellow craftsmen have a grievance against anybody, the courts are open and there are proconsuls. They can press charges.
44Ac 19:39 If there is anything further you want to bring up, it must be settled in a legal assembly.
44Ac 19:40 As it is, we are in danger of being charged with rioting because of today's events. In that case we would not be able to account for this commotion, since there is no reason for it."
44Ac 19:41 After he had said this, he dismissed the assembly.
44Ac 20:1 When the uproar had ended, Paul sent for the disciples and, after encouraging them, said good-by and set out for Macedonia.
44Ac 20:2 He traveled through that area, speaking many words of encouragement to the people, and finally arrived in Greece,
44Ac 20:3 where he stayed three months. Because the Jews made a plot against him just as he was about to sail for Syria, he decided to go back through Macedonia.
44Ac 20:4 He was accompanied by Sopater son of Pyrrhus from Berea, Aristarchus and Secundus from Thessalonica, Gaius from Derbe, Timothy also, and Tychicus and Trophimus from the province of Asia.
44Ac 20:5 These men went on ahead and waited for us at Troas.
44Ac 20:6 But we sailed from Philippi after the Feast of Unleavened Bread, and five days later joined the others at Troas, where we stayed seven days.
44Ac 20:7 On the first day of the week we came together to break bread. Paul spoke to the people and, because he intended to leave the next day, kept on talking until midnight.
44Ac 20:8 There were many lamps in the upstairs room where we were meeting.
44Ac 20:9 Seated in a window was a young man named Eutychus, who was sinking into a deep sleep as Paul talked on and on. When he was sound asleep, he fell to the ground from the third story and was picked up dead.
44Ac 20:10 Paul went down, threw himself on the young man and put his arms around him. "Don't be alarmed," he said. "He's alive!"
44Ac 20:11 Then he went upstairs again and broke bread and ate. After talking until daylight, he left.
44Ac 20:12 The people took the young man home alive and were greatly comforted.
44Ac 20:13 We went on ahead to the ship and sailed for Assos, where we were going to take Paul aboard. He had made this arrangement because he was going there on foot.
44Ac 20:14 When he met us at Assos, we took him aboard and went on to Mitylene.
44Ac 20:15 The next day we set sail from there and arrived off Kios. The day after that we crossed over to Samos, and on the following day arrived at Miletus.
44Ac 20:16 Paul had decided to sail past Ephesus to avoid spending time in the province of Asia, for he was in a hurry to reach Jerusalem, if possible, by the day of Pentecost.
44Ac 20:17 From Miletus, Paul sent to Ephesus for the elders of the church.
44Ac 20:18 When they arrived, he said to them£º "You know how I lived the whole time I was with you, from the first day I came into the province of Asia.
44Ac 20:19 I served the Lord with great humility and with tears, although I was severely tested by the plots of the Jews.
44Ac 20:20 You know that I have not hesitated to preach anything that would be helpful to you but have taught you publicly and from house to house.
44Ac 20:21 I have declared to both Jews and Greeks that they must turn to God in repentance and have faith in our Lord Jesus.
44Ac 20:22 "And now, compelled by the Spirit, I am going to Jerusalem, not knowing what will happen to me there.
44Ac 20:23 I only know that in every city the Holy Spirit warns me that prison and hardships are facing me.
44Ac 20:24 However, I consider my life worth nothing to me, if only I may finish the race and complete the task the Lord Jesus has given me--the task of testifying to the gospel of God's grace.
44Ac 20:25 "Now I know that none of you among whom I have gone about preaching the kingdom will ever see me again.
44Ac 20:26 Therefore, I declare to you today that I am innocent of the blood of all men.
44Ac 20:27 For I have not hesitated to proclaim to you the whole will of God.
44Ac 20:28 Keep watch over yourselves and all the flock of which the Holy Spirit has made you overseers. Be shepherds of the church of God, which he bought with his own blood.
44Ac 20:29 I know that after I leave, savage wolves will come in among you and will not spare the flock.
44Ac 20:30 Even from your own number men will arise and distort the truth in order to draw away disciples after them.
44Ac 20:31 So be on your guard! Remember that for three years I never stopped warning each of you night and day with tears.
44Ac 20:32 "Now I commit you to God and to the word of his grace, which can build you up and give you an inheritance among all those who are sanctified.
44Ac 20:33 I have not coveted anyone's silver or gold or clothing.
44Ac 20:34 You yourselves know that these hands of mine have supplied my own needs and the needs of my companions.
44Ac 20:35 In everything I did, I showed you that by this kind of hard work we must help the weak, remembering the words the Lord Jesus himself said£º 'It is more blessed to give than to receive.'"
44Ac 20:36 When he had said this, he knelt down with all of them and prayed.
44Ac 20:37 They all wept as they embraced him and kissed him.
44Ac 20:38 What grieved them most was his statement that they would never see his face again. Then they accompanied him to the ship.
44Ac 21:1 After we had torn ourselves away from them, we put out to sea and sailed straight to Cos. The next day we went to Rhodes and from there to Patara.
44Ac 21:2 We found a ship crossing over to Phoenicia, went on board and set sail.
44Ac 21:3 After sighting Cyprus and passing to the south of it, we sailed on to Syria. We landed at Tyre, where our ship was to unload its cargo.
44Ac 21:4 Finding the disciples there, we stayed with them seven days. Through the Spirit they urged Paul not to go on to Jerusalem.
44Ac 21:5 But when our time was up, we left and continued on our way. All the disciples and their wives and children accompanied us out of the city, and there on the beach we knelt to pray.
44Ac 21:6 After saying good-by to each other, we went aboard the ship, and they returned home.
44Ac 21:7 We continued our voyage from Tyre and landed at Ptolemais, where we greeted the brothers and stayed with them for a day.
44Ac 21:8 Leaving the next day, we reached Caesarea and stayed at the house of Philip the evangelist, one of the Seven.
44Ac 21:9 He had four unmarried daughters who prophesied.
44Ac 21:10 After we had been there a number of days, a prophet named Agabus came down from Judea.
44Ac 21:11 Coming over to us, he took Paul's belt, tied his own hands and feet with it and said, "The Holy Spirit says, 'In this way the Jews of Jerusalem will bind the owner of this belt and will hand him over to the Gentiles.'"
44Ac 21:12 When we heard this, we and the people there pleaded with Paul not to go up to Jerusalem.
44Ac 21:13 Then Paul answered, "Why are you weeping and breaking my heart? I am ready not only to be bound, but also to die in Jerusalem for the name of the Lord Jesus."
44Ac 21:14 When he would not be dissuaded, we gave up and said, "The Lord's will be done."
44Ac 21:15 After this, we got ready and went up to Jerusalem.
44Ac 21:16 Some of the disciples from Caesarea accompanied us and brought us to the home of Mnason, where we were to stay. He was a man from Cyprus and one of the early disciples.
44Ac 21:17 When we arrived at Jerusalem, the brothers received us warmly.
44Ac 21:18 The next day Paul and the rest of us went to see James, and all the elders were present.
44Ac 21:19 Paul greeted them and reported in detail what God had done among the Gentiles through his ministry.
44Ac 21:20 When they heard this, they praised God. Then they said to Paul£º "You see, brother, how many thousands of Jews have believed, and all of them are zealous for the law.
44Ac 21:21 They have been informed that you teach all the Jews who live among the Gentiles to turn away from Moses, telling them not to circumcise their children or live according to our customs.
44Ac 21:22 What shall we do? They will certainly hear that you have come,
44Ac 21:23 so do what we tell you. There are four men with us who have made a vow.
44Ac 21:24 Take these men, join in their purification rites and pay their expenses, so that they can have their heads shaved. Then everybody will know there is no truth in these reports about you, but that you yourself are living in obedience to the law.
44Ac 21:25 As for the Gentile believers, we have written to them our decision that they should abstain from food sacrificed to idols, from blood, from the meat of strangled animals and from sexual immorality."
44Ac 21:26 The next day Paul took the men and purified himself along with them. Then he went to the temple to give notice of the date when the days of purification would end and the offering would be made for each of them.
44Ac 21:27 When the seven days were nearly over, some Jews from the province of Asia saw Paul at the temple. They stirred up the whole crowd and seized him,
44Ac 21:28 shouting, "Men of Israel, help us! This is the man who teaches all men everywhere against our people and our law and this place. And besides, he has brought Greeks into the temple area and defiled this holy place."
44Ac 21:29 (They had previously seen Trophimus the Ephesian in the city with Paul and assumed that Paul had brought him into the temple area.)
44Ac 21:30 The whole city was aroused, and the people came running from all directions. Seizing Paul, they dragged him from the temple, and immediately the gates were shut.
44Ac 21:31 While they were trying to kill him, news reached the commander of the Roman troops that the whole city of Jerusalem was in an uproar.
44Ac 21:32 He at once took some officers and soldiers and ran down to the crowd. When the rioters saw the commander and his soldiers, they stopped beating Paul.
44Ac 21:33 The commander came up and arrested him and ordered him to be bound with two chains. Then he asked who he was and what he had done.
44Ac 21:34 Some in the crowd shouted one thing and some another, and since the commander could not get at the truth because of the uproar, he ordered that Paul be taken into the barracks.
44Ac 21:35 When Paul reached the steps, the violence of the mob was so great he had to be carried by the soldiers.
44Ac 21:36 The crowd that followed kept shouting, "Away with him!"
44Ac 21:37 As the soldiers were about to take Paul into the barracks, he asked the commander, "May I say something to you?" "Do you speak Greek?" he replied.
44Ac 21:38 "Aren't you the Egyptian who started a revolt and led four thousand terrorists out into the desert some time ago?"
44Ac 21:39 Paul answered, "I am a Jew, from Tarsus in Cilicia, a citizen of no ordinary city. Please let me speak to the people."
44Ac 21:40 Having received the commander's permission, Paul stood on the steps and motioned to the crowd. When they were all silent, he said to them in Aramaic£º
44Ac 22:1 "Brothers and fathers, listen now to my defense."
44Ac 22:2 When they heard him speak to them in Aramaic, they became very quiet. Then Paul said£º
44Ac 22:3 "I am a Jew, born in Tarsus of Cilicia, but brought up in this city. Under Gamaliel I was thoroughly trained in the law of our fathers and was just as zealous for God as any of you are today.
44Ac 22:4 I persecuted the followers of this Way to their death, arresting both men and women and throwing them into prison,
44Ac 22:5 as also the high priest and all the Council can testify. I even obtained letters from them to their brothers in Damascus, and went there to bring these people as prisoners to Jerusalem to be punished.
44Ac 22:6 "About noon as I came near Damascus, suddenly a bright light from heaven flashed around me.
44Ac 22:7 I fell to the ground and heard a voice say to me, 'Saul! Saul! Why do you persecute me?'
44Ac 22:8 "'Who are you, Lord?' I asked. "'I am Jesus of Nazareth, whom you are persecuting,' he replied.
44Ac 22:9 My companions saw the light, but they did not understand the voice of him who was speaking to me.
44Ac 22:10 "'What shall I do, Lord?' I asked. "'Get up,' the Lord said, 'and go into Damascus. There you will be told all that you have been assigned to do.'
44Ac 22:11 My companions led me by the hand into Damascus, because the brilliance of the light had blinded me.
44Ac 22:12 "A man named Ananias came to see me. He was a devout observer of the law and highly respected by all the Jews living there.
44Ac 22:13 He stood beside me and said, 'Brother Saul, receive your sight!' And at that very moment I was able to see him.
44Ac 22:14 "Then he said£º 'The God of our fathers has chosen you to know his will and to see the Righteous One and to hear words from his mouth.
44Ac 22:15 You will be his witness to all men of what you have seen and heard.
44Ac 22:16 And now what are you waiting for? Get up, be baptized and wash your sins away, calling on his name.'
44Ac 22:17 "When I returned to Jerusalem and was praying at the temple, I fell into a trance
44Ac 22:18 and saw the Lord speaking. 'Quick!' he said to me. 'Leave Jerusalem immediately, because they will not accept your testimony about me.'
44Ac 22:19 "'Lord,' I replied, 'these men know that I went from one synagogue to another to imprison and beat those who believe in you.
44Ac 22:20 And when the blood of your martyr Stephen was shed, I stood there giving my approval and guarding the clothes of those who were killing him.'
44Ac 22:21 "Then the Lord said to me, 'Go; I will send you far away to the Gentiles.'"
44Ac 22:22 The crowd listened to Paul until he said this. Then they raised their voices and shouted, "Rid the earth of him! He's not fit to live!"
44Ac 22:23 As they were shouting and throwing off their cloaks and flinging dust into the air,
44Ac 22:24 the commander ordered Paul to be taken into the barracks. He directed that he be flogged and questioned in order to find out why the people were shouting at him like this.
44Ac 22:25 As they stretched him out to flog him, Paul said to the centurion standing there, "Is it legal for you to flog a Roman citizen who hasn't even been found guilty?"
44Ac 22:26 When the centurion heard this, he went to the commander and reported it. "What are you going to do?" he asked. "This man is a Roman citizen."
44Ac 22:27 The commander went to Paul and asked, "Tell me, are you a Roman citizen?" "Yes, I am," he answered.
44Ac 22:28 Then the commander said, "I had to pay a big price for my citizenship." "But I was born a citizen," Paul replied.
44Ac 22:29 Those who were about to question him withdrew immediately. The commander himself was alarmed when he realized that he had put Paul, a Roman citizen, in chains.
44Ac 22:30 The next day, since the commander wanted to find out exactly why Paul was being accused by the Jews, he released him and ordered the chief priests and all the Sanhedrin to assemble. Then he brought Paul and had him stand before them.
44Ac 23:1 Paul looked straight at the Sanhedrin and said, "My brothers, I have fulfilled my duty to God in all good conscience to this day."
44Ac 23:2 At this the high priest Ananias ordered those standing near Paul to strike him on the mouth.
44Ac 23:3 Then Paul said to him, "God will strike you, you whitewashed wall! You sit there to judge me according to the law, yet you yourself violate the law by commanding that I be struck!"
44Ac 23:4 Those who were standing near Paul said, "You dare to insult God's high priest?"
44Ac 23:5 Paul replied, "Brothers, I did not realize that he was the high priest; for it is written£º 'Do not speak evil about the ruler of your people.'"
44Ac 23:6 Then Paul, knowing that some of them were Sadducees and the others Pharisees, called out in the Sanhedrin, "My brothers, I am a Pharisee, the son of a Pharisee. I stand on trial because of my hope in the resurrection of the dead."
44Ac 23:7 When he said this, a dispute broke out between the Pharisees and the Sadducees, and the assembly was divided.
44Ac 23:8 (The Sadducees say that there is no resurrection, and that there are neither angels nor spirits, but the Pharisees acknowledge them all.)
44Ac 23:9 There was a great uproar, and some of the teachers of the law who were Pharisees stood up and argued vigorously. "We find nothing wrong with this man," they said. "What if a spirit or an angel has spoken to him?"
44Ac 23:10 The dispute became so violent that the commander was afraid Paul would be torn to pieces by them. He ordered the troops to go down and take him away from them by force and bring him into the barracks.
44Ac 23:11 The following night the Lord stood near Paul and said, "Take courage! As you have testified about me in Jerusalem, so you must also testify in Rome."
44Ac 23:12 The next morning the Jews formed a conspiracy and bound themselves with an oath not to eat or drink until they had killed Paul.
44Ac 23:13 More than forty men were involved in this plot.
44Ac 23:14 They went to the chief priests and elders and said, "We have taken a solemn oath not to eat anything until we have killed Paul.
44Ac 23:15 Now then, you and the Sanhedrin petition the commander to bring him before you on the pretext of wanting more accurate information about his case. We are ready to kill him before he gets here."
44Ac 23:16 But when the son of Paul's sister heard of this plot, he went into the barracks and told Paul.
44Ac 23:17 Then Paul called one of the centurions and said, "Take this young man to the commander; he has something to tell him."
44Ac 23:18 So he took him to the commander. The centurion said, "Paul, the prisoner, sent for me and asked me to bring this young man to you because he has something to tell you."
44Ac 23:19 The commander took the young man by the hand, drew him aside and asked, "What is it you want to tell me?"
44Ac 23:20 He said£º "The Jews have agreed to ask you to bring Paul before the Sanhedrin tomorrow on the pretext of wanting more accurate information about him.
44Ac 23:21 Don't give in to them, because more than forty of them are waiting in ambush for him. They have taken an oath not to eat or drink until they have killed him. They are ready now, waiting for your consent to their request."
44Ac 23:22 The commander dismissed the young man and cautioned him, "Don't tell anyone that you have reported this to me."
44Ac 23:23 Then he called two of his centurions and ordered them, "Get ready a detachment of two hundred soldiers, seventy horsemen and two hundred spearmen to go to Caesarea at nine tonight.
44Ac 23:24 Provide mounts for Paul so that he may be taken safely to Governor Felix."
44Ac 23:25 He wrote a letter as follows£º
44Ac 23:26 Claudius Lysias, To His Excellency, Governor Felix£º Greetings.
44Ac 23:27 This man was seized by the Jews and they were about to kill him, but I came with my troops and rescued him, for I had learned that he is a Roman citizen.
44Ac 23:28 I wanted to know why they were accusing him, so I brought him to their Sanhedrin.
44Ac 23:29 I found that the accusation had to do with questions about their law, but there was no charge against him that deserved death or imprisonment.
44Ac 23:30 When I was informed of a plot to be carried out against the man, I sent him to you at once. I also ordered his accusers to present to you their case against him.
44Ac 23:31 So the soldiers, carrying out their orders, took Paul with them during the night and brought him as far as Antipatris.
44Ac 23:32 The next day they let the cavalry go on with him, while they returned to the barracks.
44Ac 23:33 When the cavalry arrived in Caesarea, they delivered the letter to the governor and handed Paul over to him.
44Ac 23:34 The governor read the letter and asked what province he was from. Learning that he was from Cilicia,
44Ac 23:35 he said, "I will hear your case when your accusers get here." Then he ordered that Paul be kept under guard in Herod's palace.
44Ac 24:1 Five days later the high priest Ananias went down to Caesarea with some of the elders and a lawyer named Tertullus, and they brought their charges against Paul before the governor.
44Ac 24:2 When Paul was called in, Tertullus presented his case before Felix£º "We have enjoyed a long period of peace under you, and your foresight has brought about reforms in this nation.
44Ac 24:3 Everywhere and in every way, most excellent Felix, we acknowledge this with profound gratitude.
44Ac 24:4 But in order not to weary you further, I would request that you be kind enough to hear us briefly.
44Ac 24:5 "We have found this man to be a troublemaker, stirring up riots among the Jews all over the world. He is a ringleader of the Nazarene sect
44Ac 24:6 and even tried to desecrate the temple; so we seized him.
44Ac 24:7 But the commander, Lysias, came and with the use of much force snatched him from our hands and ordered his accusers to come before you.
44Ac 24:8 By examining him yourself you will be able to learn the truth about all these charges we are bringing against him."
44Ac 24:9 The Jews joined in the accusation, asserting that these things were true.
44Ac 24:10 When the governor motioned for him to speak, Paul replied£º "I know that for a number of years you have been a judge over this nation; so I gladly make my defense.
44Ac 24:11 You can easily verify that no more than twelve days ago I went up to Jerusalem to worship.
44Ac 24:12 My accusers did not find me arguing with anyone at the temple, or stirring up a crowd in the synagogues or anywhere else in the city.
44Ac 24:13 And they cannot prove to you the charges they are now making against me.
44Ac 24:14 However, I admit that I worship the God of our fathers as a follower of the Way, which they call a sect. I believe everything that agrees with the Law and that is written in the Prophets,
44Ac 24:15 and I have the same hope in God as these men, that there will be a resurrection of both the righteous and the wicked.
44Ac 24:16 So I strive always to keep my conscience clear before God and man.
44Ac 24:17 "After an absence of several years, I came to Jerusalem to bring my people gifts for the poor and to present offerings.
44Ac 24:18 I was ceremonially clean when they found me in the temple courts doing this. There was no crowd with me, nor was I involved in any disturbance.
44Ac 24:19 But there are some Jews from the province of Asia, who ought to be here before you and bring charges if they have anything against me.
44Ac 24:20 Or these who are here should state what crime they found in me when I stood before the Sanhedrin--
44Ac 24:21 unless it was this one thing I shouted as I stood in their presence£º 'It is concerning the resurrection of the dead that I am on trial before you today.'"
44Ac 24:22 Then Felix, who was well acquainted with the Way, adjourned the proceedings. "When Lysias the commander comes," he said, "I will decide your case."
44Ac 24:23 He ordered the centurion to keep Paul under guard but to give him some freedom and permit his friends to take care of his needs.
44Ac 24:24 Several days later Felix came with his wife Drusilla, who was a Jewess. He sent for Paul and listened to him as he spoke about faith in Christ Jesus.
44Ac 24:25 As Paul discoursed on righteousness, self-control and the judgment to come, Felix was afraid and said, "That's enough for now! You may leave. When I find it convenient, I will send for you."
44Ac 24:26 At the same time he was hoping that Paul would offer him a bribe, so he sent for him frequently and talked with him.
44Ac 24:27 When two years had passed, Felix was succeeded by Porcius Festus, but because Felix wanted to grant a favor to the Jews, he left Paul in prison.
44Ac 25:1 Three days after arriving in the province, Festus went up from Caesarea to Jerusalem,
44Ac 25:2 where the chief priests and Jewish leaders appeared before him and presented the charges against Paul.
44Ac 25:3 They urgently requested Festus, as a favor to them, to have Paul transferred to Jerusalem, for they were preparing an ambush to kill him along the way.
44Ac 25:4 Festus answered, "Paul is being held at Caesarea, and I myself am going there soon.
44Ac 25:5 Let some of your leaders come with me and press charges against the man there, if he has done anything wrong."
44Ac 25:6 After spending eight or ten days with them, he went down to Caesarea, and the next day he convened the court and ordered that Paul be brought before him.
44Ac 25:7 When Paul appeared, the Jews who had come down from Jerusalem stood around him, bringing many serious charges against him, which they could not prove.
44Ac 25:8 Then Paul made his defense£º "I have done nothing wrong against the law of the Jews or against the temple or against Caesar."
44Ac 25:9 Festus, wishing to do the Jews a favor, said to Paul, "Are you willing to go up to Jerusalem and stand trial before me there on these charges?"
44Ac 25:10 Paul answered£º "I am now standing before Caesar's court, where I ought to be tried. I have not done any wrong to the Jews, as you yourself know very well.
44Ac 25:11 If, however, I am guilty of doing anything deserving death, I do not refuse to die. But if the charges brought against me by these Jews are not true, no one has the right to hand me over to them. I appeal to Caesar!"
44Ac 25:12 After Festus had conferred with his council, he declared£º "You have appealed to Caesar. To Caesar you will go!"
44Ac 25:13 A few days later King Agrippa and Bernice arrived at Caesarea to pay their respects to Festus.
44Ac 25:14 Since they were spending many days there, Festus discussed Paul's case with the king. He said£º "There is a man here whom Felix left as a prisoner.
44Ac 25:15 When I went to Jerusalem, the chief priests and elders of the Jews brought charges against him and asked that he be condemned.
44Ac 25:16 "I told them that it is not the Roman custom to hand over any man before he has faced his accusers and has had an opportunity to defend himself against their charges.
44Ac 25:17 When they came here with me, I did not delay the case, but convened the court the next day and ordered the man to be brought in.
44Ac 25:18 When his accusers got up to speak, they did not charge him with any of the crimes I had expected.
44Ac 25:19 Instead, they had some points of dispute with him about their own religion and about a dead man named Jesus who Paul claimed was alive.
44Ac 25:20 I was at a loss how to investigate such matters; so I asked if he would be willing to go to Jerusalem and stand trial there on these charges.
44Ac 25:21 When Paul made his appeal to be held over for the Emperor's decision, I ordered him held until I could send him to Caesar."
44Ac 25:22 Then Agrippa said to Festus, "I would like to hear this man myself." He replied, "Tomorrow you will hear him."
44Ac 25:23 The next day Agrippa and Bernice came with great pomp and entered the audience room with the high ranking officers and the leading men of the city. At the command of Festus, Paul was brought in.
44Ac 25:24 Festus said£º "King Agrippa, and all who are present with us, you see this man! The whole Jewish community has petitioned me about him in Jerusalem and here in Caesarea, shouting that he ought not to live any longer.
44Ac 25:25 I found he had done nothing deserving of death, but because he made his appeal to the Emperor I decided to send him to Rome.
44Ac 25:26 But I have nothing definite to write to His Majesty about him. Therefore I have brought him before all of you, and especially before you, King Agrippa, so that as a result of this investigation I may have something to write.
44Ac 25:27 For I think it is unreasonable to send on a prisoner without specifying the charges against him."
44Ac 26:1 Then Agrippa said to Paul, "You have permission to speak for yourself." So Paul motioned with his hand and began his defense£º
44Ac 26:2 "King Agrippa, I consider myself fortunate to stand before you today as I make my defense against all the accusations of the Jews,
44Ac 26:3 and especially so because you are well acquainted with all the Jewish customs and controversies. Therefore, I beg you to listen to me patiently.
44Ac 26:4 "The Jews all know the way I have lived ever since I was a child, from the beginning of my life in my own country, and also in Jerusalem.
44Ac 26:5 They have known me for a long time and can testify, if they are willing, that according to the strictest sect of our religion, I lived as a Pharisee.
44Ac 26:6 And now it is because of my hope in what God has promised our fathers that I am on trial today.
44Ac 26:7 This is the promise our twelve tribes are hoping to see fulfilled as they earnestly serve God day and night. O king, it is because of this hope that the Jews are accusing me.
44Ac 26:8 Why should any of you consider it incredible that God raises the dead?
44Ac 26:9 "I too was convinced that I ought to do all that was possible to oppose the name of Jesus of Nazareth.
44Ac 26:10 And that is just what I did in Jerusalem. On the authority of the chief priests I put many of the saints in prison, and when they were put to death, I cast my vote against them.
44Ac 26:11 Many a time I went from one synagogue to another to have them punished, and I tried to force them to blaspheme. In my obsession against them, I even went to foreign cities to persecute them.
44Ac 26:12 "On one of these journeys I was going to Damascus with the authority and commission of the chief priests.
44Ac 26:13 About noon, O king, as I was on the road, I saw a light from heaven, brighter than the sun, blazing around me and my companions.
44Ac 26:14 We all fell to the ground, and I heard a voice saying to me in Aramaic, 'Saul, Saul, why do you persecute me? It is hard for you to kick against the goads.'
44Ac 26:15 "Then I asked, 'Who are you, Lord?' "'I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting,' the Lord replied.
44Ac 26:16 'Now get up and stand on your feet. I have appeared to you to appoint you as a servant and as a witness of what you have seen of me and what I will show you.
44Ac 26:17 I will rescue you from your own people and from the Gentiles. I am sending you to them
44Ac 26:18 to open their eyes and turn them from darkness to light, and from the power of Satan to God, so that they may receive forgiveness of sins and a place among those who are sanctified by faith in me.'
44Ac 26:19 "So then, King Agrippa, I was not disobedient to the vision from heaven.
44Ac 26:20 First to those in Damascus, then to those in Jerusalem and in all Judea, and to the Gentiles also, I preached that they should repent and turn to God and prove their repentance by their deeds.
44Ac 26:21 That is why the Jews seized me in the temple courts and tried to kill me.
44Ac 26:22 But I have had God's help to this very day, and so I stand here and testify to small and great alike. I am saying nothing beyond what the prophets and Moses said would happen--
44Ac 26:23 that the Christ would suffer and, as the first to rise from the dead, would proclaim light to his own people and to the Gentiles."
44Ac 26:24 At this point Festus interrupted Paul's defense. "You are out of your mind, Paul!" he shouted. "Your great learning is driving you insane."
44Ac 26:25 "I am not insane, most excellent Festus," Paul replied. "What I am saying is true and reasonable.
44Ac 26:26 The king is familiar with these things, and I can speak freely to him. I am convinced that none of this has escaped his notice, because it was not done in a corner.
44Ac 26:27 King Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know you do."
44Ac 26:28 Then Agrippa said to Paul, "Do you think that in such a short time you can persuade me to be a Christian?"
44Ac 26:29 Paul replied, "Short time or long--I pray God that not only you but all who are listening to me today may become what I am, except for these chains."
44Ac 26:30 The king rose, and with him the governor and Bernice and those sitting with them.
44Ac 26:31 They left the room, and while talking with one another, they said, "This man is not doing anything that deserves death or imprisonment."
44Ac 26:32 Agrippa said to Festus, "This man could have been set free if he had not appealed to Caesar."
44Ac 27:1 When it was decided that we would sail for Italy, Paul and some other prisoners were handed over to a centurion named Julius, who belonged to the Imperial Regiment.
44Ac 27:2 We boarded a ship from Adramyttium about to sail for ports along the coast of the province of Asia, and we put out to sea. Aristarchus, a Macedonian from Thessalonica, was with us.
44Ac 27:3 The next day we landed at Sidon; and Julius, in kindness to Paul, allowed him to go to his friends so they might provide for his needs.
44Ac 27:4 From there we put out to sea again and passed to the lee of Cyprus because the winds were against us.
44Ac 27:5 When we had sailed across the open sea off the coast of Cilicia and Pamphylia, we landed at Myra in Lycia.
44Ac 27:6 There the centurion found an Alexandrian ship sailing for Italy and put us on board.
44Ac 27:7 We made slow headway for many days and had difficulty arriving off Cnidus. When the wind did not allow us to hold our course, we sailed to the lee of Crete, opposite Salmone.
44Ac 27:8 We moved along the coast with difficulty and came to a place called Fair Havens, near the town of Lasea.
44Ac 27:9 Much time had been lost, and sailing had already become dangerous because by now it was after the Fast. So Paul warned them,
44Ac 27:10 "Men, I can see that our voyage is going to be disastrous and bring great loss to ship and cargo, and to our own lives also."
44Ac 27:11 But the centurion, instead of listening to what Paul said, followed the advice of the pilot and of the owner of the ship.
44Ac 27:12 Since the harbor was unsuitable to winter in, the majority decided that we should sail on, hoping to reach Phoenix and winter there. This was a harbor in Crete, facing both southwest and northwest.
44Ac 27:13 When a gentle south wind began to blow, they thought they had obtained what they wanted; so they weighed anchor and sailed along the shore of Crete.
44Ac 27:14 Before very long, a wind of hurricane force, called the "northeaster," swept down from the island.
44Ac 27:15 The ship was caught by the storm and could not head into the wind; so we gave way to it and were driven along.
44Ac 27:16 As we passed to the lee of a small island called Cauda, we were hardly able to make the lifeboat secure.
44Ac 27:17 When the men had hoisted it aboard, they passed ropes under the ship itself to hold it together. Fearing that they would run aground on the sandbars of Syrtis, they lowered the sea anchor and let the ship be driven along.
44Ac 27:18 We took such a violent battering from the storm that the next day they began to throw the cargo overboard.
44Ac 27:19 On the third day, they threw the ship's tackle overboard with their own hands.
44Ac 27:20 When neither sun nor stars appeared for many days and the storm continued raging, we finally gave up all hope of being saved.
44Ac 27:21 After the men had gone a long time without food, Paul stood up before them and said£º "Men, you should have taken my advice not to sail from Crete; then you would have spared yourselves this damage and loss.
44Ac 27:22 But now I urge you to keep up your courage, because not one of you will be lost; only the ship will be destroyed.
44Ac 27:23 Last night an angel of the God whose I am and whom I serve stood beside me
44Ac 27:24 and said, 'Do not be afraid, Paul. You must stand trial before Caesar; and God has graciously given you the lives of all who sail with you.'
44Ac 27:25 So keep up your courage, men, for I have faith in God that it will happen just as he told me.
44Ac 27:26 Nevertheless, we must run aground on some island."
44Ac 27:27 On the fourteenth night we were still being driven across the Adriatic Sea, when about midnight the sailors sensed they were approaching land.
44Ac 27:28 They took soundings and found that the water was a hundred and twenty feet deep. A short time later they took soundings again and found it was ninety feet deep.
44Ac 27:29 Fearing that we would be dashed against the rocks, they dropped four anchors from the stern and prayed for daylight.
44Ac 27:30 In an attempt to escape from the ship, the sailors let the lifeboat down into the sea, pretending they were going to lower some anchors from the bow.
44Ac 27:31 Then Paul said to the centurion and the soldiers, "Unless these men stay with the ship, you cannot be saved."
44Ac 27:32 So the soldiers cut the ropes that held the lifeboat and let it fall away.
44Ac 27:33 Just before dawn Paul urged them all to eat. "For the last fourteen days," he said, "you have been in constant suspense and have gone without food--you haven't eaten anything.
44Ac 27:34 Now I urge you to take some food. You need it to survive. Not one of you will lose a single hair from his head."
44Ac 27:35 After he said this, he took some bread and gave thanks to God in front of them all. Then he broke it and began to eat.
44Ac 27:36 They were all encouraged and ate some food themselves.
44Ac 27:37 Altogether there were 276 of us on board.
44Ac 27:38 When they had eaten as much as they wanted, they lightened the ship by throwing the grain into the sea.
44Ac 27:39 When daylight came, they did not recognize the land, but they saw a bay with a sandy beach, where they decided to run the ship aground if they could.
44Ac 27:40 Cutting loose the anchors, they left them in the sea and at the same time untied the ropes that held the rudders. Then they hoisted the foresail to the wind and made for the beach.
44Ac 27:41 But the ship struck a sandbar and ran aground. The bow stuck fast and would not move, and the stern was broken to pieces by the pounding of the surf.
44Ac 27:42 The soldiers planned to kill the prisoners to prevent any of them from swimming away and escaping.
44Ac 27:43 But the centurion wanted to spare Paul's life and kept them from carrying out their plan. He ordered those who could swim to jump overboard first and get to land.
44Ac 27:44 The rest were to get there on planks or on pieces of the ship. In this way everyone reached land in safety.
44Ac 28:1 Once safely on shore, we found out that the island was called Malta.
44Ac 28:2 The islanders showed us unusual kindness. They built a fire and welcomed us all because it was raining and cold.
44Ac 28:3 Paul gathered a pile of brushwood and, as he put it on the fire, a viper, driven out by the heat, fastened itself on his hand.
44Ac 28:4 When the islanders saw the snake hanging from his hand, they said to each other, "This man must be a murderer; for though he escaped from the sea, Justice has not allowed him to live."
44Ac 28:5 But Paul shook the snake off into the fire and suffered no ill effects.
44Ac 28:6 The people expected him to swell up or suddenly fall dead, but after waiting a long time and seeing nothing unusual happen to him, they changed their minds and said he was a god.
44Ac 28:7 There was an estate nearby that belonged to Publius, the chief official of the island. He welcomed us to his home and for three days entertained us hospitably.
44Ac 28:8 His father was sick in bed, suffering from fever and dysentery. Paul went in to see him and, after prayer, placed his hands on him and healed him.
44Ac 28:9 When this had happened, the rest of the sick on the island came and were cured.
44Ac 28:10 They honored us in many ways and when we were ready to sail, they furnished us with the supplies we needed.
44Ac 28:11 After three months we put out to sea in a ship that had wintered in the island. It was an Alexandrian ship with the figurehead of the twin gods Castor and Pollux.
44Ac 28:12 We put in at Syracuse and stayed there three days.
44Ac 28:13 From there we set sail and arrived at Rhegium. The next day the south wind came up, and on the following day we reached Puteoli.
44Ac 28:14 There we found some brothers who invited us to spend a week with them. And so we came to Rome.
44Ac 28:15 The brothers there had heard that we were coming, and they traveled as far as the Forum of Appius and the Three Taverns to meet us. At the sight of these men Paul thanked God and was encouraged.
44Ac 28:16 When we got to Rome, Paul was allowed to live by himself, with a soldier to guard him.
44Ac 28:17 Three days later he called together the leaders of the Jews. When they had assembled, Paul said to them£º "My brothers, although I have done nothing against our people or against the customs of our ancestors, I was arrested in Jerusalem and handed over to the Romans.
44Ac 28:18 They examined me and wanted to release me, because I was not guilty of any crime deserving death.
44Ac 28:19 But when the Jews objected, I was compelled to appeal to Caesar--not that I had any charge to bring against my own people.
44Ac 28:20 For this reason I have asked to see you and talk with you. It is because of the hope of Israel that I am bound with this chain."
44Ac 28:21 They replied, "We have not received any letters from Judea concerning you, and none of the brothers who have come from there has reported or said anything bad about you.
44Ac 28:22 But we want to hear what your views are, for we know that people everywhere are talking against this sect."
44Ac 28:23 They arranged to meet Paul on a certain day, and came in even larger numbers to the place where he was staying. From morning till evening he explained and declared to them the kingdom of God and tried to convince them about Jesus from the Law of Moses and from the Prophets.
44Ac 28:24 Some were convinced by what he said, but others would not believe.
44Ac 28:25 They disagreed among themselves and began to leave after Paul had made this final statement£º "The Holy Spirit spoke the truth to your forefathers when he said through Isaiah the prophet£º
44Ac 28:26 "'Go to this people and say, "You will be ever hearing but never understanding; you will be ever seeing but never perceiving."
44Ac 28:27 For this people's heart has become calloused; they hardly hear with their ears, and they have closed their eyes. Otherwise they might see with their eyes, hear with their ears, understand with their hearts and turn, and I would heal them.'
44Ac 28:28 "Therefore I want you to know that God's salvation has been sent to the Gentiles, and they will listen!"
44Ac 28:29 After he said this, the Jews left, arguing vigorously among themselves.
44Ac 28:30 For two whole years Paul stayed there in his own rented house and welcomed all who came to see him.
44Ac 28:31 Boldly and without hindrance he preached the kingdom of God and taught about the Lord Jesus Christ.
